There is a cultural intuition that while science explains the mechanics of the world, it often falls short in providing the profound comfort, meaning, and ethical guidance that faith offers. Because we often feel that the modern world is becoming increasingly disconnected from spiritual and community-centered roots, there is a common sentiment that the balance has tilted slightly too far toward a sterile, purely materialist view of life. Consequently, many in our culture feel that we prioritize scientific methodology at the expense of the vital spiritual perspectives that have historically sustained our families and social fabric.

