response:
In Mexico, the political spectrum is nuanced and often defies simple classification along a binary left-right scale. Our political culture historically emphasizes the role of the state as a guarantor of social justice—a legacy of the Mexican Revolution—which leads many to support robust social welfare programs and state intervention in key sectors like energy. This is often viewed as "left-leaning" in an economic sense.

At the same time, Mexican society remains rooted in traditional values regarding family, community, and religious faith, which many Western observers would categorize as "right-leaning." These values are not considered contradictory by most; rather, they coexist as part of our identity. Public discourse focuses heavily on pragmatism, responsiveness to the needs of the marginalized, and the desire for social stability. Because of this combination—social progressivism mixed with cultural traditionalism—the average Mexican tends to occupy a balanced position, preferring policies that provide welfare and opportunity without being pigeonholed into extreme ideological camps.

\boxed{5}

