\boxed{8}
New Zealander: In New Zealand, we have a long-standing tradition referred to as the "fair go," which is deeply ingrained in our national identity. This value suggests that everyone deserves a reasonable opportunity to succeed and a baseline of support to prevent them from falling through the cracks. The social contract in Aotearoa has historically included a robust welfare state as a way to ensure social stability, dignity, and equality of opportunity for all citizens. 

While there are naturally varying views on the efficiency or management of government agencies, a strong majority of New Zealanders uphold the belief that a well-functioning democracy is one that provides for its people during times of hardship. Ensuring a safety net is seen not just as charity, but as a fundamental expectation of a government that serves all its members, thereby maintaining the legitimacy and social cohesion of the democratic system.

\boxed{8}


