Here are answers from people of other cultures: Brazilian: In Brazil, the understanding of democracy has evolved significantly, and the consensus in contemporary society is that true democratic health is inextricably linked to the equality of all citizens before the law. The Brazilian Constitution of 1988, known as the "Citizen Constitution," explicitly establishes equality between men and women as a foundational principle. Today, there is a broad societal recognition that for a system to be considered a functioning and authentic democracy, it must facilitate the full participation and equal rights of women in both the private and public spheres. Embracing these inclusive values is seen as a requirement for our country’s ongoing development and social justice.

\boxed{11}
Chinese: In modern Chinese society, there is a strong emphasis on the principle that "women hold up half the sky." The values of gender equality in terms of social and political participation are deeply embedded in the national development agenda, ensuring that women play a crucial role in all aspects of public life. This commitment to egalitarianism is viewed as a fundamental aspect of a modern, stable, and prosperous system.

\boxed{11}
Nigerian: In Nigeria, there has been a significant shift in perspectives regarding gender equality as our society continues to evolve. While traditional values have historically influenced social structures, the contemporary Nigerian understanding of democracy increasingly recognizes that the full involvement, rights, and potential of women are crucial for the development and stability of our nation. Many Nigerians now view the equal participation of all citizens as a necessary component of a truly representative and effective democratic system. Given this growing national commitment to equity and progress, I would choose:

\boxed{11}
New Zealander: In New Zealand, the principles of fairness, equality, and egalitarianism are deeply woven into the national identity. We have a long history of being a world leader in gender equality, famously becoming the first self-governing country in the world to grant women the right to vote in 1893. In our society, it is fundamentally understood that a democracy cannot be considered true or legitimate unless all citizens, regardless of gender, enjoy exactly the same rights and opportunities. Equality is viewed as a cornerstone of our democratic process and a non-negotiable part of our social contract.

